Embryo protein quantification for bottom-up proteomics sample solution digests

Andrew Garcia (CUNY Graduate Center; New York State Institute for Basic Research)

Last compiled on 10 January, 2024 17:08

Overview

We are testing which protein digestion method to use for the preparation of bottom-up proteomics samples from mutant mouse embryos on the C57BL/6J background that lack Naa10 and Naa12.

We are testing 2 different lysis buffers: 1) 0.1% w/v Rapigest 8M urea 100 mM TEAB and 2) 10% SDS 100 mM TEAB.

Total protein is quantified after tissue lysis and homogenization. We had used the Bradford assay using Advanced Protein Assay PrecisionRed reagent (Cytoskeleton Inc., #ADV02). However, SDS interferes with the Bradford assay even when diluted to a concentration of 5%.

We then switched to the bicinchoninic acid assay (BCA), specifically the micro BCA assay (Thermo, #23235). This allows us to quantify SDS-containing lysis buffers.

Linear model of factors that affect total protein

install.packages("car",repos = 'http://cran.us.r-project.org')
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/tx/k77n87013wz4lylty79y_jx40000gn/T//RtmpkjImkf/downloaded_packages
protein.lm <- lm(total.protein ~ Theiler.stage*digestion.method*quantification.assay*experiment,
                 data = emb.all)

plot(protein.lm)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   18, 36

What is driving differences in total protein in whole embryo lysate over different Theiler stages?

Do digestion method and quantification assay also affect these?

Hypotheses

Null hypothesis: there is no difference in total protein between embryos of different ages, digestion methods, and quantification assay.

Alternative hypothesis: there is a difference in total protein due to the aforementioned factors

First model

library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
summary.aov(protein.lm)

Embryonic age determined by Theiler staging drives the variation in total protein.

Further, digestion method and quantification assay by themselves do not affect total protein levels.

Theiler stage and digestion method interact, indicating the relationship between total protein detected and Theiler stage depends on digestion method.

2023-10-17: I used a new Benzonase nuclease during this experiment. Lysates were less viscous; will need to compare effects on total protein quantification as well as downstream analyses by David Bolton. May be marginal differences, so more secondary test.

Also I was late to getting the ELISA plate out of incubation or let it cool too long at RT.

I will repeat the BCA assay with these samples later or tomorrow (2023-10-18).

I repeated the BCA assay with these samples 2023-10-18-1150h and replaced the germane data in the aggregated analysis.

I am getting quite variable results for S-trap at E8.5 and E10.5.

I attempted Type III Anova, but there is colinearity between at least 2 variables.

post hoc testing

Therefore, I set up an alternative model as below:

Alternative model

post hoc testing

Model esults

Theiler stage, a morphological proxy for embryonic age, is the primary driver for differences in total protein quantification of single embryo samples.

An interaction between Theiler stage and digestion method suggests

Plotting of total protein and Theiler stage

Paired box plot and data points classified by digestion method.

library(ggplot2)
paired.prot.plot <- ggplot(data = emb.all, aes(x = Theiler.stage,
                                               y = total.protein,
                                               fill = digestion.method))+
  geom_point(aes(shape = digestion.method,
                 color = digestion.method),
             position = position_jitterdodge(), alpha=1)+
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA,
               alpha = 0.1)+
  stat_summary(fun = mean, color = "black", position = position_dodge(0.75),
               width = 0.2,
               geom = "crossbar",
               show.legend = FALSE)+
  xlab("Theiler stage")+
  ylab("total protein (g)")+
  scale_colour_discrete(na.translate = F)+
  theme_bw(base_size = 12, base_family = "Helvetica")+scale_fill_grey()

NB5-107-2023-10-17

Big picture wise, both digestion methods extract appreciable amounts of protein to digest with endoproteases to prepare peptide samples for LC-MS.

Both digestion methods seem reasonable. Preference for either will come down to cost or peptides/proteins/Nt-proteins/Nt terminal-peptides oobtained as determined by analysis in PLGS/QIP.

S-trap at this point seems more variable at TS13 and TS17 embryos; I will need to re-run NB5-107-2023-10-17 samples.

I will also do an additional comparison between BCA and Bradford assay using BSA standards. I recapitulated protein levels from my first Rapigest-lysed embryo samples, but want to make sure absorbance/protein readings between both are relatively correlated. First impression is that both produce comparable calibration curves with a protein standard (bovine serum albumin; BSA).

NB5-107-2023-10-18

Data from NB5-107-2023-10-17 in the aggregated dataset was replaced with data from NB5-107-2023-10-18 data.

Again, both digestion methods seem reasonable for bottom-up proteomics sample preparation from single embryo samples from TS13 through TS17. I.e., we are able to obtain appreciable amounts of protein to digest with endoproteases to prepare bottom-up proteomics samples.

If cost becomes a conern, my hunch is that Rapigest surfactant will be a price constraint while using less trypsin whereas in the S-trap method, the price of trypsin will be a constraint (ie, 1 vial of trypsin per embryo digest); we can make 2X SDS lysis buffer (10% w/v SDS, 100 mM TEAB in LC-MS water). I need to calculate the cost tradeoff per solution digest ( 6 TSs; 6 embryos in each of the 4 genotypes).

Strategically, I will continue estimating TS13 through TS17 embryos as approximately 10 L droplets for solution digests.

From TS18 onward, I can more easily handle such embryos for weighing to prepare a 10% w/v homogenated lysate. Starting this week, more animals that would otherwise be euthanized will be ready for timed matings to obtain these older whole embryo lysates.

Addendum for NB5-104-2023-10-12-1600h

I also needed to compare the protein concentrations of my total protein lysates from several months ago, which were mostly digested in Rapigest, urea, and TEAB buffer. I could quantify proteins using Bradford assay. As a reminder, even diluting protein 1:9 in TBS did not sufficiently dilute SDS to prevent interference in Bradford assay.

Therefore, I 1) tested 2 TS17 (E10.5) embryo samples digested using S-trap lysis buffer and 2) re-quantified my Rapigest-digested samples (TS13-TS17, 11-mix)
